    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-08-05T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-08-05T12:00:00-05:00" n="518"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d518">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860D.00/8–548: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smith</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret   urgent</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-08-05T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 5, 1948—8 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1530. Though thus far refraining from directly attacking new Finnish
                        Government,<note n="1" xml:id="d518fn1">On July 29, 1948, Fagerholm had
                        constituted a new Finnish Cabinet. All of the Ministers except Enckell, who
                        continued as Minister of Foreign Affairs, were Social Democrats.</note>
                    Moscow’s obvious displeasure over Communists complete exclusion is shown by
                    considerable space given Soviet press last few days to highly critical comment
                    by foreign Communist sources, above all in Finland itself (for example <gloss
                        target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss>s 1520 August 4, and 1523 August 5<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d518fn2">Neither printed.</note>). Apart from general
                    considerations which may still call for policy of “moderation” (see <gloss
                        target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss> 1282 July 9), Soviets probably hope
                    Fagerholm Government’s narrow basis of support will prevent it from surviving
                    long, and its eventual demise will consequently impair position social democracy
                    in that country.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 1530, repeated Helsinki 59.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
